{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-9620cfc2efb1fa13", "type": "tool_result", "content": "1\tRĀG CLASSIFICATION OF TAGORE SONGS USING SYMBOLIC MUSIC\n2\tNOTATION AND NOVEL WEIGHTED DISTANCE MEASURES\n3\tCHANDAN MISRA AND SWARUP CHATTOPADHYAY\n4\t\n5\tarXiv:2607.07241v2 [cs.SD] 9 Jul 2026\n6\t\n7\tAbstract. Rabindra Sangeet, the body of songs written and composed by Rabindranath Tagore,\n8\toccupies a distinctive position in Indian music by combining poetic expression with melodic ideas\n9\tdrawn from Hindustani rāgs, Bengali folk traditions, tappa, kı̄rtan, Baul music, and Western tunes.\n10\tAlthough many Tagore songs are associated with rāg labels provided by Tagore himself or preserved\n11\tin authoritative notational traditions, rāg identification remains challenging because the songs often\n12\treflect creative freedom rather than strict adherence to classical rāg grammar.\n13\tThis paper formulates rāg identification in Rabindra Sangeet as a supervised classification problem\n14\tusing symbolic music-sheet notations from Swarabitan. Since large-scale annotated audio or music\n15\tdatasets for Rabindra Sangeet are not readily available, this study constructs a rāg-labelled symbolic\n16\tdataset from notated Tagore songs. The work investigates Euclidean distance and cosine similarity for\n17\trāg classification and introduces a weighted Euclidean distance measure that assigns greater importance\n18\tto notes belonging to characteristic rāg sequences such as arohana and avarohana. Applied within a\n19\tk-nearest-neighbour framework, the proposed measure improves rāg classification by better capturing\n20\trāg-specific melodic identity.\n21\t\n22\t1. Introduction\n23\tIndian music has evolved through a continuous interaction between classical discipline, regional expression, devotional imagination, poetic thought, and cultural practice. The Hindustani classical tradition,\n24\twith its highly developed concepts of rāg and tāla, provides a sophisticated framework for organizing\n25\tmelody, rhythm, mood, and performance. At the same time, Indian musical culture has never remained\n26\trestricted to the boundaries of formal classical grammar. It has continuously interacted with folk traditions, devotional forms, literary movements, theatre, dance, and regional musical practices.\n27\tWithin this rich musical landscape, Rabindra Sangeet occupies a distinctive and culturally significant\n28\tposition. Composed by Rabindranath Tagore, the Nobel Laureate poet, composer, philosopher, and\n29\tartist, Rabindra Sangeet represents one of the most important song traditions of Bengal. These songs\n30\tform an integral part of Bengali cultural life in India and Bangladesh and continue to hold a central\n31\tplace in artistic, social, educational, and devotional contexts.\n32\tMusically, Tagore’s songs draw from a wide range of sources. Many compositions reveal the influence of\n33\tHindustani classical rāgs and tāla-based structures, while others reflect the melodic character of tappa,\n34\tkı̄rtan, Baul, Bengali folk music, devotional idioms, and Western tunes [1–3]. Tagore did not merely\n35\treproduce these traditions in a fixed or mechanical manner. Instead, he adapted and transformed them\n36\taccording to the expressive needs of the text, the emotional situation of the song, and his own artistic\n37\tvision. As a result, Rabindra Sangeet retains a deep connection with Indian musical traditions while\n38\tdeveloping an independent musical identity.\n39\tAlthough, the tonal colours of rāgs often provide the emotional foundation of the songs, the use of\n40\trāg in Rabindra Sangeet is not always identical to its use in formal Hindustani classical performance. In\n41\tmany cases, Tagore employed rāg elements with creative freedom, allowing poetic meaning and emotional\n42\texpression to guide the musical structure. Some Tagore songs closely follow the characteristic structure\n43\tand melodic behaviour of a particular rāg. Others combine features of two or more rāgs, while some\n44\tsongs are traditionally associated with a rāg but do not strictly follow its grammatical framework [4, 5].\n45\tThe compositional structure of Rabindra Sangeet further increases the difficulty of rāg identification.\n46\tFor a beginner or non-specialist listener, recognizing the rāg from a Tagore song is often difficult because\n47\tthe song may not present the rāg in a direct or conventional manner. A single composition may contain\n48\ta long sequence of notes, repeated melodic phrases, expressive variations, and movements that do not\n49\talways correspond to the strict grammar of a classical rāg. Consequently, predicting the rāg basis of a\n50\tRabindra Sangeet composition is a challenging task. Existing approaches to rāg classification, which are\n51\tDate: June 1, 2017, accepted December 7, 2017.\n52\t2000 Mathematics Subject Classification. Primary xxx, yyyy; Secondary xxxx, yyyy.\n53\tKey words and phrases. Dxxx gxxx, Axxx gxxx.\n54\t1\n55\t\n56\t\f2\n57\t\n58\tCHANDAN MISRA AND SWARUP CHATTOPADHYAY\n59\t\n60\toften designed for classical music performances, cannot be directly applied to Rabindra Sangeet without\n61\tcareful adaptation. This is because Tagore’s songs are highly diverse in melodic construction.\n62\tRāg identification is important for several computational music tasks, including music learning, music\n63\tinformation retrieval, mood-based classification, recommendation, and computational music generation.\n64\tIn the context of Rabindra Sangeet, this task becomes particularly meaningful because many songs are\n65\tassociated with rāg labels, yet their melodic structures often differ from the strict grammar of Hindustani\n66\tclassical compositions. Therefore, identifying the underlying rāg of a Tagore song requires examining its\n67\tmelodic behaviour, including the use of Āroh, Avroh, dominant notes, omitted notes, and the relative\n68\timportance of notes within the composition.\n69\tHowever, this diversity does not make the problem unsuitable for supervised learning. On the contrary,\n70\tRabindra Sangeet provides an interesting setting for supervised rāg classification because many songs are\n71\tassociated with rāg labels provided by Tagore himself or preserved in authoritative notational traditions.\n72\tThese rāg labels offer a meaningful ground truth for computational analysis. Therefore, the present\n73\tstudy formulates rāg identification as a supervised classification problem, where labelled Tagore songs\n74\tare used to train a model that can learn rāg-specific melodic behaviour from symbolic note sequences.\n75\tAlthough rāg identification can naturally be formulated as a supervised learning problem, the availability of suitable annotated datasets remains a major limitation in the context of Rabindra Sangeet.\n76\tIn many music classification tasks, annotated audio or music datasets [6–8] with reliable class labels\n77\tare used to train supervised models [9–12]. However, such large-scale labelled datasets are not readily\n78\tavailable for Rabindra Sangeet. This creates a significant barrier to applying existing data-driven rāg\n79\tclassification techniques directly to Tagore songs.\n80\tTo address this limitation, the present work relies on symbolic music-sheet notations rather than\n81\tannotated audio recordings. The primary source of these notations is Swarabitan, the collection of\n82\tnotated songs written and composed by Rabindranath Tagore. Swarabitan contains a large body of\n83\tRabindra Sangeet compositions along with their musical notations, and therefore provides a structured\n84\tsymbolic representation of the melodic content of Tagore songs.\n85\tThese notated compositions are useful for computational analysis because the melodic content of\n86\teach song can be converted into note sequences and note-frequency distributions. Since many of these\n87\tcompositions are associated with rāg labels provided by Tagore himself or preserved in authoritative\n88\tnotational traditions, they can be used to construct a supervised learning dataset. In this way, the\n89\tabsence of a ready-made annotated audio dataset is addressed by preparing a rāg-labelled symbolic\n90\tdataset from notated Rabindra Sangeet compositions.\n91\tIn this work, we prepare a supervised symbolic dataset of 1000 rāg-labelled Tagore songs from Swarabitan. Each sample in the dataset corresponds to the note-frequency distribution of a composition and is\n92\tassociated with its appropriate rāg label. The construction of this dataset is an important contribution of\n93\tthe work, as it provides a structured ground truth for supervised rāg classification in Rabindra Sangeet.\n94\tA natural approach to rāg identification is to compare a given composition with other compositions\n95\twhose rāg labels are already known. If two compositions are musically similar, they may be expected\n96\tto share similar rāg characteristics. Therefore, an unknown or test composition can be assigned the rāg\n97\tlabel of its nearest labelled compositions using a distance or similarity-based classifier. In this direction, Euclidean distance and cosine similarity provide simple and widely used measures for quantifying\n98\tsimilarity between compositions represented through note-frequency features.\n99\tHowever, standard distance and similarity measures may not be sufficient for Rabindra Sangeet.\n100\tPreliminary observations show that Euclidean distance and cosine similarity can sometimes produce\n101\tcontradictory or misleading results. In particular, they may assign high similarity or low distance not\n102\tonly to compositions belonging to the same rāg, but also to compositions belonging to different rāgs.\n103\tThis happens because small variations in individual note frequencies may strongly affect the similarity\n104\tscore, while the musically important role of characteristic notes may not be adequately captured. Thus,\n105\ttwo compositions may appear numerically similar even when their rāg identities are different.\n106\tTo address this limitation, the present study introduces a rāg-aware weighted Euclidean distance\n107\tmeasure. The main idea is to assign greater importance to notes that belong to the prescribed Āroh and\n108\tAvroh of a rāg, and comparatively lower importance to other notes. This weighting allows the distance\n109\tmeasure to better reflect rāg-specific melodic identity rather than treating all note-frequency differences\n110\tequally. When used with a k-nearest-neighbour classifier, the weighted distance measure helps improve\n111\tthe distinction between compositions belonging to similar and dissimilar rāgs.\n112\t\n113\t\fSHORT TITLE\n114\t\n115\t3\n116\t\n117\t2. Dataset\n118\t2.1. Dataset Generation. As mentioned earlier, Tagore’s complete collection of songs consists of approximately 2200 compositions. This collection of songs is known as Geetobitan (The Garden of Songs),\n119\twhile their musical notations are published separately in Swarabitan (The Garden of Notes). Swarabitan,\n120\ta book series comprising around 60 volumes, contains the notations of songs from Geetobitan written in\n121\tthe Akarmatrik notation system.\n122\tFor the present study, the dataset was created by randomly selecting 1000 compositions from Swarabitan. The notes of each selected composition were manually stored in a CSV file along with the corresponding rāg label. Therefore, each sample in the dataset represents a single composition from Swarabitan.\n123\tSince Rabindrasangeet is based on the Rāgs of Hindustani Sangeet (with a little blend of folk genres\n124\tlike Baul and Kirtan), the notes of the compositions span over three octaves or Saptak s, namely the\n125\tmiddle or Madhya, upper or Taar, and lower octave or Mandra Saptak. The rāgs also follow the same\n126\tĀroh and Avroh notes of Hindutani Sangeet which depict the sequence of permissible notes in ascending\n127\tand descending pattern respectively. Additionally, they aid in describing the rag’s mood. Each octave\n128\tconsists of 12 notes which generates 36 probable notes for each composition. We have indexed each note\n129\twith an integer starting from 1 and ending at 36 as given in Table 1.\n130\tSuddha\n131\tSuddha\n132\tKomal\n133\tKomal\n134\tShadaj\n135\tMadhyam\n136\tRishabh Rishabh Gandhar Gandhar\n137\t(S, S, Ṡ)\n138\t(M , M , Ṁ )\n139\t(r, r, ṙ) (R, R, Ṙ) (g, g, ġ) (G, G, Ġ) ˙\n140\t˙\n141\t˙\n142\t˙ 17, 29\n143\tIndices 1, 13, 25 2, 14, 26 3,˙ 15, 27 4,˙ 16, 28 5,\n144\t6, 18, 30\n145\tKomal\n146\tSuddha\n147\tSuddha\n148\tTivr\n149\tKomal\n150\tPancham\n151\tDhaivat\n152\tDhaivat\n153\tNishad\n154\tNishad\n155\tNote Madhyam\n156\t(P , P , Ṗ )\n157\t˙ (D, D, Ḋ) (n, n, ṅ) (N , N , Ṅ )\n158\t(m, m, ṁ) ˙\n159\t(d, d, d)\n160\t˙\n161\t˙\n162\t˙ 22, 34 11,\n163\t˙ 24, 36\n164\tIndices 7, 19, 31 8, 20, 32 9,˙ 21, 33 10,\n165\t23, 35 12,\n166\tNote\n167\t\n168\tTable 1. Notes and indices of lower octave or Mandra Saptak (indices 1 to 12), Middle\n169\toctave or Madhya Saptak (indices 13 to 24), and upper octave or Taar Saptak (indices\n170\t25 to 36)\n171\tOnce such mapping is established we generate the note table for each such 1000 compositions. To\n172\tcreate the final dataset we generate the frequency distribution of each composition which serves as 36\n173\tindependent variables and obtain the rāg of the composition for the dependent variable. Figure 1 shows\n174\tthe overall process of mapping a composition to a frequency table.\n175\t2.2. Summary of the Dataset. As previously mentioned the dataset consists of 36 features corresponding to 36 notes spanning across three octaves for each sample and there are 1000 such samples\n176\thave been considered for our experimental evaluation. We labeled each such sample with the rāg of the\n177\tcomposition which have also been extracted manually from the book while creating the dataset and can\n178\tbe considered as a ground truth. There are 239 unique rāgs identified in the entire dataset and more than\n179\t50% samples (545 compositions) belong to 227 least frequent rāgs having number of compositions less\n180\tthan 20. Table 1 shows the frequencies of unique rāgs with increasing number of compositions. In other\n181\twords Table 1 answers the query How many unique rāgs are there having n number of compositions?,\n182\tfor example.\n183\tWhile Table 2a summarizes the distribution of the less frequent rāgs in the dataset, Table 2b presents\n184\tthe opposite view by listing the 12 most frequent rāg labels. This information is important because\n185\trāgs with very few compositions may not provide sufficient samples to capture a reliable note-frequency\n186\tpattern or average distribution for that particular rāg.\n187\tIn Table 2b, we also provide the corresponding Thaat of each rāg. In Hindustani classical music,\n188\ta Thaat refers to the parent scale or melodic framework used in Pt. Vishnu Narayan Bhatkhande’s\n189\tsystem for classifying rāgs according to their note structure. Including the Thaat information helps the\n190\treader understand the broader melodic family to which a rāg belongs. It is also useful for interpreting\n191\tsimilarities between rāgs, since rāgs belonging to the same Thaat may share similar note structures.\n192\tHowever, the entries Baul and Kirtan are marked as NA because they are not classified as rāgs under\n193\tthe Bhatkhande Thaat system. Rather, they represent folk and devotional musical traditions that occur\n194\tfrequently in Rabindra Sangeet but do not necessarily follow a fixed Āroh–Avroh structure associated\n195\twith a specific Hindustani classical rāg. Therefore, they are retained in the dataset as musical-category\n196\tlabels rather than being assigned to a particular Thaat.\n197\t\n198\t\f4\n199\t\n200\tCHANDAN MISRA AND SWARUP CHATTOPADHYAY\n201\t\n202\t16\n203\t\n204\t14\n205\t\n206\t14\n207\t\n208\t13\n209\t\n210\t13\n211\t\n212\t13\n213\t\n214\t21\n215\t\n216\t21\n217\t\n218\t21\n219\t\n220\t23\n221\t\n222\t25\n223\t\n224\t25\n225\t\n226\t23\n227\t\n228\t28\n229\t\n230\t28\n231\t\n232\t26\n233\t\n234\t25\n235\t\n236\t23\n237\t\n238\t25\n239\t\n240\t25\n241\t\n242\t25\n243\t\n244\t25\n245\t\n246\t25\n247\t\n248\t25\n249\t\n250\t23\n251\t\n252\t28\n253\t\n254\t26\n255\t\n256\t25\n257\t\n258\t26\n259\t\n260\t25\n261\t\n262\t23\n263\t\n264\t25\n265\t\n266\t23\n267\t\n268\t21\n269\t\n270\t23\n271\t\n272\t21\n273\t\n274\t(b) Mapping from actual note to its corresponding integer value\n275\t\n276\t\n277\tMultimodal Voice Activity Projection for Turn-Taking in Social Robots\n278\twith Voice-Activity-Related Pretrained Encoders\n279\t\n280\tarXiv:2607.07294v1 [cs.RO] 8 Jul 2026\n281\t\n282\tAntonio Cano1,2 , Guillermo Pérez1 , Luis Merino2\n283\tAbstract— Turn-taking prediction is a key requirement for\n284\tsocial robots involved in human-human interaction, particularly in mediator settings, where the robot must anticipate\n285\tconversational dynamics rather than merely react to pauses.\n286\tThis work presents a Multimodal Voice Activity Projection\n287\t(MM-VAP) framework that extends the original audio-only\n288\tVAP formulation to synchronized audio-visual inputs while\n289\tpreserving its self-supervised future-projection objective. The\n290\tproposed approach builds on pretrained audio-visual backbones\n291\toriginally optimized for speech-related tasks and adapts them\n292\tthrough Low-Rank Adaptation to the multimodal turn-taking\n293\tproblem. After independent speaker encoding, an inter-speaker\n294\tattention stage models the relational dynamics required to\n295\tproject future voice activity. In addition, a semantic consistency\n296\tloss is introduced to regularize the 256-state output space according to higher-level dialogue activity patterns. Experiments\n297\ton NoXi and NoXi+J showed improvements over the current\n298\tbaselines, particularly for some turn-taking events. Additional\n299\tevaluation on the Haru EDR corpus further supported the\n300\tsuitability of this direction for mediation-oriented human-robot\n301\tinteraction.\n302\tThe source codes and pretrained models are available at\n303\thttps://github.com/acano15/MM-VAP.\n304\t\n305\tI. I NTRODUCTION\n306\tTurn-taking is the universal mechanism of human communication for structuring spoken interaction and coordinating\n307\tspeaker and listener roles [1]. To achieve effective Human–Robot Interaction (HRI), conversational robots must account for this human-like coordination across verbal and nonverbal behavior. In social robotics, interaction is inherently\n308\tturn-based [2], so accurate interpretation of conversational\n309\tflow and timing is necessary to enable fluid and effective\n310\tcommunication.\n311\tThis work extends previous research [3] within the Haru\n312\tsocial robot project, specifically when Haru acts as an\n313\tembodied social mediator that supports human-human interactions [4]–[6]. In this scenario, Haru is not conceived as\n314\tone of the main interlocutors, but instead as a background\n315\tsocial mediator (Fig. 1) that helps regulate conversational\n316\tflow, balance participation, manage silences, and support\n317\tsocio-emotional behaviors such as active listening, engagement, and empathy. This mediator role motivates the present\n318\t1 Antonio Cano and Guillermo Perez are with 4i Intelligent Insights,\n319\tSeville, Spain. a.cano@4i.ai, g.perez@4i.ai\n320\t3 Antonio Cano is with Universidad de Sevilla, Seville, Spain.\n321\t\n322\tacano4@us.es\n323\t2\n324\t\n325\tLuis Merino is with Universidad Pablo de Olavide, Seville, Spain.\n326\t\n327\tlmercab@upo.es\n328\t3 Randy Gomez is with Honda Research Institute Japan, Saitama, Japan.\n329\t\n330\tr.gomez@jp.honda-ri.com\n331\t\n332\tand Randy Gomez3\n333\t\n334\tFig. 1: Haru operating as social mediator in two-party\n335\tinteraction setting [8].\n336\tresearch toward enabling Haru to better understand and\n337\tmanage the ongoing interaction, with particular emphasis on\n338\thow the conversational floor evolves over time and anticipate\n339\twhen it may change.\n340\tNevertheless, current dialogue systems are not yet sufficiently accurate at managing turn-taking, and this remains an\n341\tactive area of research because users frequently experience\n342\tthe effects of such failures. Typical problems include interruptions or overlaps due to speaking before or after a turn\n343\thas ended, unnaturally long delays caused by late responses,\n344\tand incorrect answers resulting from misunderstanding the\n345\tuser’s input. Furthermore, because human communication is\n346\tinherently multimodal [7], these limitations, together with the\n347\tlack of multimodal perception skills, may cause the robot to\n348\tgaze at the wrong person or respond to irrelevant background\n349\tspeech.\n350\tAddressing this issue requires a structured view of how\n351\tturns are formed, maintained, and exchanged during interaction. In conversation analysis, spoken interaction is\n352\tdescribed in terms of Turn-Constructional Units (TCUs),\n353\twhose possible completion defines a Transition-Relevant\n354\tPlace (TRP) that may lead to a turn shift, a turn hold,\n355\tor floor closure. Most industrial systems remain reactive\n356\t[9], using heuristic silence-based rules to detect the Endof-Turn (EoT), normally around 700 ms [10]. Studies in\n357\tdialogue systems and dialogue robots [10]–[13] have shown\n358\tthat such approaches are insufficient for modeling conversational dynamics because speakers may produce longer pauses\n359\twithin their own turn, known as Inter-Pausal Units (IPUs)\n360\t[14]. Human turn-taking in conversations follows a different\n361\tprinciple than current Spoken Dialogue Systems (SDSs).\n362\tA key distinction is that humans do not simply wait for\n363\texplicit cues indicating that the interlocutor is ready to yield\n364\t\n365\tAccepted preprint. This manuscript has been accepted for presentation at the 35th IEEE International Conference on Robot and Human\n366\tInteractive Communication (RO-MAN 2026). Acceptance notification date: 30 May 2026. The final published version is pending.\n367\t\n368\t\fthe floor; instead, they continuously predict ongoing events\n369\tand adapt their role as listener or speaker accordingly. This\n370\tgenuinely predictive behavior is supported by the temporal\n371\tconstraints of speech generation: producing speech typically\n372\trequires around 600 ms to 1500 ms [15], [16], and the time\n373\tbetween turns, as well known as Floor Transfer Offset (FTO),\n374\tusually occurs around 200 ms of silence (in some cultures\n375\tmay approach 0 ms [17]). This temporal mismatch indicates\n376\tthat turn-taking depends on prediction, with multimodal cues\n377\tguiding anticipation of TRPs and coordinating responses\n378\twith minimal delay.\n379\tInspired by this behavior, Predictive Turn-Taking Models (PTTMs) have been proposed as neural models that\n380\tcontinuously project future conversational activity at frame\n381\tlevel, mostly in two-party spoken interaction [10]. Among\n382\tcurrent approaches, Voice Activity Projection (VAP) [18]\n383\tis positioned as one of the most effective formulations for\n384\tcontinuous turn-taking prediction, including real-time implementations. VAP projects frame-by-frame the voice activity\n385\t(VA) of two speakers and models their interaction dynamics\n386\tto predict turn-taking events. More recently, multimodal\n387\textensions of VAP have become an active and promising\n388\tresearch direction [9], [19]–[21], where the incorporation\n389\tof non-verbal information offers further opportunities for\n390\timprovement, despite the challenges that still remain in\n391\tpractical spoken dialogue system environments.\n392\tTo contribute to this research line, this work proposes\n393\ta transformers-based MultiModal Voice Activity Projection\n394\t(MM-VAP) model built on specialized pretrained encoders.\n395\tThe main contributions are the following:\n396\t• An audio-visual MM-VAP architecture that integrates VArelated pretrained backbones while preserving their native representational and fusion capabilities for improved\n397\tVA projection.\n398\t• A parameter-efficient adaptation strategy based on LowRank Adaptation for specializing the encoders to the\n399\ttarget turn-taking task.\n400\t• Improved performance on mediation-relevant turn-taking\n401\tstates, highlighting the benefits of the proposed pipeline.\n402\t• The first application of MM-VAP in a robotics context,\n403\twith an empirical evaluation of the proposed approach for\n404\tpredictive turn-taking in the Haru social mediator setting.\n405\tII. R ELATED W ORK\n406\tTurn-taking prediction has been extensively studied in\n407\tSDS, HRI, and, more recently, in VAP-based approaches.\n408\tThis section reviews the most relevant prior work and the\n409\tkey considerations that motivated the presented approach.\n410\tRecent multimodal speech and language research [22]–\n411\t[28] has shown that large pretrained backbones can be\n412\tefficiently adapted with Low-Rank Adaptation (LoRA), allowing transfer of knowledge to more specific tasks by\n413\tupdating only a small subset of parameters instead of the\n414\tentire model. At the same time, multimodal specialization\n415\t\n416\tstill depends on attention mechanisms to model cross-modal\n417\tdependencies. Based on this, special attention is given to\n418\ttwo backbones: TalkNet [29], which uses cross-attention\n419\tand self-attention for Active Speaker Detection (ASD), and\n420\tWhisperFlamingo [30], which combines pretrained Whisper\n421\tand AV-HuBERT with gated cross-attention for multilingual\n422\tAudio Visual Speech Recognition (AVSR).\n423\tWithin the VAP research line, [18] introduced VAP as\n424\ta self-supervised prediction problem that outputs the VA\n425\tof two speakers. The original model combines an encoder\n426\tbased on a pretrained CPC backbone operating on the raw\n427\taudio waveform with a second encoder that incorporates the\n428\tcurrent VA frame and its history, followed by a transformer\n429\tthat projects future VA. This formulation has remained a\n430\tcentral reference for turn-taking modeling in SDSs and\n431\tmost subsequent studies have preserved its core idea with\n432\tonly minor modifications. For example, [31] extended VAP\n433\tto three-party interaction by reducing the projection space\n434\tto two bins per speaker, [32] adapted it to binary and\n435\tthree-class backchannel (BC) prediction and [33] modified\n436\tthe loss function by incorporating BC and EoT terms to\n437\tbalance multitask objectives. Regarding multilinguality, [34]\n438\tshowed that monolingual models generalize poorly to unseen\n439\tlanguages in contrast with training on multiple languages,\n440\twhose performance was comparable to the original languagespecific implementations. Complementing this finding, [35]\n441\targued that those cross-lingual differences are better explained by dataset discrepancies, particularly inconsistencies\n442\tin speech segmentation labels, than language itself. Beyond\n443\toffline benchmarks, VAP has also shown practical value,\n444\tas its continuous frame-level formulation and lightweight\n445\tinference make it suitable for real-time (RT) implementation.\n446\tFor instance, [36] demonstrated the feasibility of continuous\n447\tturn-taking prediction by shortening the transformer input\n448\t(1s), with only limited performance degradation. However,\n449\taccording to [13], its effectiveness still depends on sensor\n450\treliability and synchronization quality.\n451\tIn the field of robotics, turn-taking has shown promising\n452\timprovements over conventional strategies. The main HRI\n453\treference remains [37], in which one of the speakers is\n454\treplaced by the robot’s own voice so that VAP could provide RT turn-taking event predictions for floor management,\n455\tinterruptions and BC. More recently, [38] reformulated the\n456\ttraining with noisy data to improve robustness and latency\n457\tin RT environment and validated it on a dialogue robot\n458\tdeployed in a shopping mall.\n459\tConcerning multimodal VAP, only a few studies have been\n460\treported so far, all of them extending the original acoustic\n461\tframework to additional modalities under formulations close\n462\tto the original VAP design. The first multimodal VAP solution was presented in [39] with the addition of a non-verbal\n463\tbranch based on gaze, action units, head pose, and articularpoint features. Their results showed that multimodality improved performance across predictive events. This work was\n464\tlater extended in [19] through a broader experimental study,\n465\t\n466\tAccepted preprint. This manuscript has been accepted for presentation at the 35th IEEE International Conference on Robot and Human\n467\tInteractive Communication (RO-MAN 2026). Acceptance notification date: 30 May 2026. The final published version is pending.\n468\t\n469\t\fFig. 2: Proposed MM-VAP architecture for dyadic interaction overview. Blue and red paths indicate the flow from raw inputs\n470\tto latent representations for Speaker 1 and Speaker 2. Snowflake and flame symbols denote frozen and trainable parameters.\n471\tThe bottom-right panel shows how the target turn-taking events are derived from voice activity patterns within wt∆t .\n472\tthe addition of an overlap prediction metric and the evaluation across multiple corpora. An analogous feature-based\n473\tdirection was followed in [9], with facial feature positioning\n474\tas the strongest visual contributor, resulting in improved\n475\tperformance over audio-only baselines. Nevertheless, both\n476\tapproaches relied on engineered descriptors rather than\n477\tmodel-based feature extraction. Moving toward multimodal\n478\tbackbone-oriented solutions, the unique approach identified\n479\twas [20], in which the authors replaced the hand-crafted\n480\tfacial descriptors with pretrained audio (original CPC) and a\n481\tfacial expression encoder (DEFER). However, the selected\n482\tencoders remained generic and their pretraining was not\n483\trelated to voice activity, which reduced their potential for\n484\tVAP. In addition, because the approach used two separate\n485\tencoders, the inter-modal relation had to be learned from\n486\tscratch.\n487\tMotivated by these limitations, the present work investigates whether multimodal VAP can benefit from specialized\n488\tspeech-activity backbones integrated into its inter-modal\n489\tattention mechanism to obtain richer, more task-relevant\n490\tmultimodal representations.\n491\tIII. P ROPOSED M ETHOD\n492\tThis section describes the proposed multimodal VAP\n493\t(MM-VAP) framework and its complete pipeline, from synchronized audio-visual input sequences to VA and VAP\n494\tstate projection estimation and final inference of turn-taking\n495\tevents.\n496\tA. Multimodal Voice Activity Projection (MM-VAP)\n497\tVAP was formally defined [18] as the task of predicting\n498\t(projecting) the future VA binary state (active/inactive) of\n499\t\n500\teach interlocutor in a dialogue. MM-VAP extends the standard definition by incorporating data from multiple modalities, in this case, audio and visual signals. The projection is\n501\tformulated over a finite temporal horizon ∆t that spans from\n502\tthe current time step t to a future point t + ∆t. Within this\n503\tinterval, the future binary VA of both speakers is considered\n504\tjointly, so that future VA is modeled as a single projection\n505\twindow, wt∆t , that represents the future trajectory of the\n506\tdialogue and the joint VA of both speakers as a whole. The\n507\tchoice of the window length involves a balance because it\n508\tshould be long enough to be able to capture relevant turntaking information but no longer than it attempts to represent\n509\texcessively complex or unnatural future interaction patterns.\n510\tAs in the original implementation, this window is divided\n511\tinto 4 heterogeneous bins per speaker. The first two bins\n512\tare shorter, representing the immediate present (now), or\n513\tnear future, and the last two bins correspond to longer bins\n514\tthat cover more distant f uture. Since the scenario involves\n515\ttwo speakers, the complete projection window is represented\n516\tby a joint space of 22N = 256 states, in which each state\n517\tcompactly covers every possible configuration of the horizon\n518\tinteraction between the two interlocutors.\n519\tB. Proposed MM-VAP model architecture\n520\tAs shown in Fig. 2, the model is organized in five stages:\n521\tpreprocessing, backbone encoding, inter-speaker attention,\n522\tprediction heads with postprocessing.\n523\tFirst, the raw audio-visual streams are segmented in the\n524\twt∆t centered at each frame step t with ∆t horizon separated\n525\tinto speaker-specific signals. For each speaker i, the audio\n526\twaveform is transformed into a spectral representation, and\n527\tthe visual stream is processed by the face detection module\n528\tthat extracts the temporally ordered sequence of cropped\n529\tface images. Then, both modalities are synchronized to the\n530\t\n531\tAccepted preprint. This manuscript has been accepted for presentation at the 35th IEEE International Conference on Robot and Human\n532\tInteractive Communication (RO-MAN 2026). Acceptance notification date: 30 May 2026. The final published version is pending.\n533\t\n534\t\fsame temporal resolution and fed together into the pretrained,\n535\tfine-tuned encoder. Inside the encoder, each modality is\n536\tfirst processed by its own corresponding modality encoder\n537\tbranch, yielding speaker representations in their respective\n538\tlatent spaces. The resulting audio and visual embeddings\n539\tare fused with the backbone’s original inter-modal attention\n540\tmechanism, producing an embedding per speaker:\n541\tHi = Attn(Ea (Xia ), Ev (Xiv )), where H i ∈ R256 and\n542\t{Qai = Ea (Xia ), Kiv = Viv = Ev (Xiv )}.\n543\tOnce each H is obtained, the model applies a second\n544\tmultihead cross-attention mechanism between both speakers,\n545\treferred to as inter-speaker attention, to learn how the current\n546\tmultimodal state of one \u0001participant influences the other.\n547\tz = Φinter-spkrs H(1) , H(2) . This stage allows the model to\n548\tencode turn-taking as a relational process, so the prediction\n549\tis conditioned on both the speaker’s current state and the\n550\tother speaker’s state. The joint representation z is then fed\n551\tto two heads: the first head estimates the multiclass VAP\n552\tstate distribution, and the second head predicts the binary\n553\tVA probabilities. Finally, these outputs are postprocessed\n554\tto compute the target turn-taking event categories from the\n555\tpredicted VAP state distribution.\n556\tC. Backbone encoders and LoRA adaptation\n557\tThe current MM-VAP solution is based on the premise that\n558\tmodeling turn-taking is equivalent to predict the evolution\n559\tof the speaker’s VA dynamics from audio-visual cues. This\n560\twork hypothesized that a pretrained encoder whose original\n561\ttask is closely related to VA would be more suitable as a\n562\tstarting point for MM-VAP than a pretrained generic multimodal encoder. Under this view, the multimodal encoder\n563\tshould provide latent representations that remain strongly\n564\taligned with speech activity and are able to preserve the\n565\ttemporal coordination between audio-visual modalities.\n566\tIn addition, the backbone selection was based on two\n567\tcriteria: first, the backbone should achieve high accuracy\n568\ton its original task related to speech activity, and second,\n569\tit should include a robust internal attention mechanism between audio-visual modalities. The architecture is modularly\n570\tdesigned, so any transformer-based backbone that satisfies\n571\tthese conditions could be integrated. In this work, TalkNet\n572\tand WhisperFlamingo were selected because they both meet\n573\tboth requirements and provide well proved pretrained multimodal encoders for ASD and AVSR respectively, which are\n574\tbased on speech activity.\n575\t0\n576\tNevertheless, their original pretrained weights, Wav\n577\t∈\n578\tRdxk , remain specialized for the original task, so an adaptation mechanism is required to redirect their representations\n579\tto the target setting. Given the size and the high variance\n580\tof the original backbones weights, fully fine-tuning the\n581\tpretrained model is computationally very inefficient, which\n582\tmotivates the use of Low-Rank Adaptation (LoRA) training\n583\tstrategy. LoRA keeps the original model weights frozen\n584\tand adds trainable low-rank matrices to selected layers to\n585\tadapt the backbone to the MM-VAP objective. This strategy\n586\t\n587\tis computationally more efficient because it approximates\n588\tthe full objective weights (∆W ) by applying the low-rank\n589\tdecomposition of the ∆W into a scalar product of two\n590\tsmaller matrices B ∈ Rdxr and A ∈ Rrxk . Formally, LoRA\n591\tdefines the adapted mapping as:\n592\tα\n593\t0\n594\t(1)\n595\tWAv = WAv\n596\t+ BA, r ≪ min(d, k),\n597\tr\n598\twhere A and B are trainable low-rank matrices, r is the\n599\tadaptation rank and α is the scaling factor. In this context,\n600\tr controls the flexibility of the adaptation to adapt to the\n601\tVAP objective and α determines how strongly that adaptation\n602\tinfluences the training.\n603\tWithin this framework, LoRA enables the specialization of\n604\tthe pretrained backbone to the MM-VAP objective by building on the capabilities acquired during its original training\n605\tphase and redirecting them toward future VA projection.\n606\tD. Zero-shot turn-taking events inference\n607\tThis work followed the original VAP Self-Supervised\n608\tLearning (SSL) approach [18], in which the training is\n609\tperformed without manual annotations of turn-taking events.\n610\tSpecifically, at each frame, the model predicts a probability\n611\tdistribution over the 256 states, and the turn-taking events are\n612\tobtained in a zero-shot manner by summing the probabilities\n613\tof the states linked to each conversational outcome. This\n614\tinterpretability is enabled by collapsing the fine-grained state\n615\tspace into a simpler bin-level representation that preserves\n616\tthe same VAP state distribution, with four possible cases:\n617\tspeaker 1 active, speaker 2 active, both active, or neither\n618\tactive. Based on this four-way representation, the aggregated\n619\tprobabilities pnow and pf uture summarize speaker activity\n620\tover the near and later regions of the projection window\n621\tand provide the basis for defining each turn-taking event as\n622\tfollows:\n623\t• Shift vs Holds (S/H): measures who are expected to\n624\ttake the floor after a mutual silence. If the same speaker\n625\tcontinues, the event is Hold; if the floor passes to the other\n626\tspeaker, it is Shift.\n627\t• Long vs Shorts (L/S): describes the duration of the utterance after a valid speaker change. Long means that the new\n628\tspeaker keeps speaking for a sustained period, whereas\n629\tShort corresponds to a brief response (Backchannel).\n630\t• Shift prediction (S-pred): checks whether the other\n631\tspeaker is likely to take the floor soon, even though the\n632\tcurrent speaker is still holding it.\n633\t• Backchannel prediction (BC-pred): measures whether\n634\tthe non-active (listener) is likely to produce a short response, without the current speaker releasing the turn.\n635\tE. Loss function\n636\tIn natural dialogue, many individual VAP state configurations are extremely rare (e.g.: alternating speech in unusual\n637\tpatterns) and the resulting distribution is therefore inherently unbalanced. Moreover, because multiple microstates\n638\tcorrespond to the same speaker-activity condition, errors\n639\t\n640\tAccepted preprint. This manuscript has been accepted for presentation at the 35th IEEE International Conference on Robot and Human\n641\tInteractive Communication (RO-MAN 2026). Acceptance notification date: 30 May 2026. The final published version is pending.\n642\t\n643\t\fbetween semantically equivalent microstate predictions do\n644\tnot usually affect the final event computation, although they\n645\tstill contribute to the optimization of the 256-state objective.\n646\tTo guide optimization toward speaker-activity patterns that\n647\tare truly relevant for event inference, an additional semantic\n648\tconsistency term (Lsem ) is incorporated into the original loss\n649\tfunction:\n650\tL = LV A + LV AP + µ · Lsem , µ ∈ [0.1, 0.2] (2)\n651\tLV AP is cross-entropy over 256 VAP microstates, LVA is\n652\tmulti-label binary cross-entropy loss for per-speaker VA\n653\toutputs, and µ is an empirically chosen coefficient that\n654\tcontrols the new loss contribution. Lsem is defined as:\n655\t\n656\t\n657\t\n658\t\n659\t0 : spkr1 active\n660\t\n661\t\n662\tX\n663\t1 : No spkrs active\n664\tpt (k) , st ∈\n665\tLsem = Et − log\n666\t\n667\t2 : Both spkrs active\n668\t\n669\t\n670\t3 : spkr2 active\n671\t\n672\tk∈Gst\n673\t\n674\t(3)\n675\twhere pt (k) is the predicted probability of microstate k at\n676\ttime t, st the semantic dialogue states and Gst the set of all\n677\tmicrostates whose current activity matches the same st .\n678\tHence, instead of only discriminating among imbalanced\n679\tand partially redundant microstates, Lsem encourages the\n680\tmodel to assign probability mass to all states that share the\n681\tcorrect dialogue meaning. From an optimization perspective,\n682\tthis term reduces the influence of rare or ambiguous states,\n683\timproves training stability, and aligns the learned VAP distribution with the speaker-activity patterns used to derive the\n684\ttarget events, leading to more robust predictions throughout\n685\ttraining.\n686\tIV. E XPERIMENTS AND RESULTS\n687\t\n688\twindow, represented through 256 states computed from four\n689\ttemporal bins per speaker (200, 400, 600, and 800 ms). The\n690\tmodel predicts future VA from synchronized audio-visual\n691\tcontext, and the resulting projections are evaluated against\n692\tthe corresponding zero-shot turn-taking events obtained from\n693\tthe VA annotations, using accuracy and F1-score.\n694\tFor all the experiments, the data are split at the session\n695\tlevel into 80 % for training, 10 % for validation, and 10\n696\t% for testing. The datasets were selected for their multilingual coverage and their suitability for the mediator-oriented\n697\tinteraction setting:\n698\t1) NoXi [40]: NOvice eXpert Interaction (NoXi) is a\n699\tmultilingual multimodal corpus of screen-mediated dyadic\n700\tinteractions between an expert and a novice. It captures natural knowledge-sharing conversations in a video-conferencelike setting, where both participants are recorded in separate\n701\trooms with synchronized audio, video, and depth streams.\n702\tThe original corpus contains 84 sessions and around 25 hours\n703\tof data collected in France, Germany, and the UK, mainly\n704\tin English, French, and German. NoXi+J [41] extends this\n705\tsetup with 48 Japanese and 18 Chinese sessions under the\n706\tsame protocol, resulting in a total of 150 sessions and about\n707\t41 hours of multimodal interaction data.\n708\t2) EDR [8]: Empathetic Dialogues with a Robot (EDR)\n709\tconsists of semi-structured speaker–listener interactions conducted in the presence of Haru, in which the robot frames\n710\teach exchange by delivering an introduction and an emotionbased prompt in English, while the humans carry the conversation (see Fig. 1). The dialogues were derived from reallife situations with 79 conversations, 214 exchanges, and 428\n711\tlabeled utterances.\n712\t\n713\tA. Experimental setup and datasets\n714\tB. Results\n715\tThe experimental protocol was based on the original\n716\tVAP framework, extending it from an acoustic-only setting\n717\tto a multimodal formulation while preserving the same\n718\tself-supervised projection objective. The input consists of\n719\tsynchronized 10s context window extracted with a 0.5s\n720\tslide, prepared according to backbone requirements: audio\n721\tencoded as Log-Mel spectrograms and the visual stream\n722\tas detected faces sequence resized to 112×112 grayscale\n723\tframes. The prediction target is set as 2s future voice activity\n724\t\n725\tLanguage\n726\tEnglish\n727\tGerman\n728\tFrench\n729\tJapanese\n730\tChinese\n731\t\n732\tBackbone\n733\tTalkNet\n734\tWhisperFlamingo\n735\tTalkNet\n736\tWhisperFlamingo\n737\tTalkNet\n738\tWhisperFlamingo\n739\tTalkNet\n740\tWhisperFlamingo\n741\tTalkNet\n742\tWhisperFlamingo\n743\t\n744\tThe following results correspond to experiments designed\n745\tto evaluate VA-related pretrained backbones adapted with\n746\tLoRA within their attention mechanisms, in comparison with\n747\tmore generic pretrained backbones and non-pretrained variants presented in Section II. All experiments were conducted\n748\tunder the same data distribution and evaluation conditions,\n749\twith particular emphasis on mediation events relevant to\n750\tVA projection. The LoRA adapter parameters were kept\n751\t\n752\tTurn-taking Events (Accuracy / F1)\n753\tS/H\n754\tS/L\n755\tS-pred\n756\tBC-pred\n757\t0.87 ± 0.03 / 0.86 ± 0.01 0.88 ± 0.01 / 0.92 ± 0.01 0.88 ± 0.01 / 0.88 ± 0.01 0.30 ± 0.01 / 0.41 ± 0.01\n758\t0.82 ± 0.08 / 0.82 ± 0.09 0.84 ± 0.02 / 0.89 ± 0.02 0.97 ± 0.04 / 0.97 ± 0.04 0.34 ± 0.02 / 0.45 ± 0.02\n759\t0.89 ± 0.01 / 0.89 ± 0.01 0.87 ± 0.01 / 0.91 ± 0.01 0.94 ± 0.01 / 0.94 ± 0.00 0.33 ± 0.01 / 0.41 ± 0.01\n760\t0.82 ± 0.04 / 0.82 ± 0.04 0.87 ± 0.01 / 0.91 ± 0.01 0.97 ± 0.02 / 0.97 ± 0.02 0.35 ± 0.02 / 0.43 ± 0.03\n761\t0.87 ± 0.03 / 0.87 ± 0.03 0.82 ± 0.03 / 0.88 ± 0.02 0.89 ± 0.05 / 0.89 ± 0.05 0.47 ± 0.03 / 0.56 ± 0.03\n762\t0.84 ± 0.07 / 0.84 ± 0.07 0.85 ± 0.01 / 0.89 ± 0.01 0.96 ± 0.03 / 0.96 ± 0.03 0.42 ± 0.03 / 0.52 ± 0.03\n763\t0.77 ± 0.01 / 0.77 ± 0.01 0.76 ± 0.01 / 0.83 ± 0.01 0.81 ± 0.01 / 0.80 ± 0.01 0.57 ± 0.01 / 0.64 ± 0.01\n764\t0.86 ± 0.03 / 0.87 ± 0.03 0.72 ± 0.01 / 0.80 ± 0.01 0.86 ± 0.02 / 0.86 ± 0.02 0.56 ± 0.03 / 0.62 ± 0.03\n765\t0.85 ± 0.01 / 0.85 ± 0.01 0.77 ± 0.01 / 0.79 ± 0.01 0.90 ± 0.01 / 0.90 ± 0.01 0.77 ± 0.01 / 0.77 ± 0.01\n766\t0.85 ± 0.01 / 0.85 ± 0.01 0.81 ± 0.04 / 0.84 ± 0.04 0.94 ± 0.01 / 0.94 ± 0.01 0.57 ± 0.01 / 0.57 ± 0.01\n767\t\n768\tTABLE I: Per-language results on the evaluated corpora. Each cell reports Acc/F1 for the corresponding turn-taking event.\n769\tAccepted preprint. This manuscript has been accepted for presentation at the 35th IEEE International Conference on Robot and Human\n770\tInteractive Communication (RO-MAN 2026). Acceptance notification date: 30 May 2026. The final published version is pending.\n771\t\n772\t\ffixed across experiments to avoid biasing the final outcome\n773\tcomparison. The selection of parameter values was based on\n774\ttheir original performance and the proximity to the original\n775\ttasks for VA projection. In consequence, α = 16 and r = 16\n776\tfor TalkNet and α = 64 and r = 32 for WhisperFlamingo,\n777\tseeking deeper adaptation. Regarding the hyperparameters,\n778\tthe models were trained for 8 epochs, a linear scheduler\n779\tfor the learning rate with initial value µ = 0.009 and the\n780\tcallbacks needed for stable optimization.\n781\tTable I summarizes the language-wise results obtained on\n782\tNoXi+J with the two main pretrained backbones adapted\n783\twith LoRA. Reported values are represented by the mean ±\n784\tstandard deviation of accuracy and F1-score over a 4-fold\n785\tcross-validation. The results show consistent performance\n786\tacross languages, with similar distribution patterns. WhisperFlamingo achieved the highest S-pred scores for English\n787\tand German, while TalkNet obtained the best S/H score for\n788\tGerman and the top BC-pred score for Chinese. In contrast,\n789\tperformance on Japanese remained the lowest overall. Across\n790\tthe remaining languages, TalkNet generally outperformed in\n791\tS/H and BC-pred metrics, whereas WhisperFlamingo yielded\n792\tsuperior results in S/L and S-pred.\n793\tTable II come from models trained with different combinations of NoXi+J languages set. In addition to the two main\n794\tpretrained backbones, a third reference model integrating\n795\tCPC for audio and 3DResNet for video was included as\n796\ta non-pretrained baseline for comparison, given its wellestablished strong performance on VA tasks. Across all\n797\tconfigurations, the pretrained variants consistently outperformed this reference. WhisperFlamingo tended to report the\n798\tstrongest S-pred values, with similar results for S/H across\n799\tboth backbones.\n800\tCorpus\n801\t\n802\tBackbone\n803\t\n804\tTurn-taking Events (F1)\n805\tS/L\n806\t\n807\tS-pred\n808\t\n809\tBC-pred\n810\t\n811\tNoXi\n812\t\n813\tCPC+3DResNet 0.64 0.70\n814\tTalkNet\n815\t0.94 0.93\n816\tWhisperFlamingo 0.97 0.91\n817\t\n818\tS/H\n819\t\n820\t0.65\n821\t0.91\n822\t0.97\n823\t\n824\t0.33\n825\t0.42\n826\t0.45\n827\t\n828\tNew NoXi+J\n829\t(Chin + Jap)\n830\t\n831\tCPC+3DResNet 0.50 0.61\n832\tTalkNet\n833\t0.84 0.82\n834\tWhisperFlamingo 0.85 0.80\n835\t\n836\t0.51\n837\t0.87\n838\t0.93\n839\t\n840\t0.55\n841\t0.62\n842\t0.66\n843\t\n844\tNoXi+J (All)\n845\t\n846\tCPC+3DResNet 0.55 0.59\n847\tTalkNet\n848\t0.85 0.85\n849\tWhisperFlamingo 0.81 0.86\n850\t\n851\t0.58\n852\t0.89\n853\t0.90\n854\t\n855\t0.39\n856\t0.62\n857\t0.44\n858\t\n859\tTABLE II: Experiments on the combined NoXi+J language\n860\tset using pretrained and baseline backbones.\n861\tTable III compares the F1-scores reported in previous\n862\trelated work on different corpora with those obtained in this\n863\tstudy. The first method’s results were limited to Shift/Hold\n864\tevents, whereas the other two are directly comparable to\n865\tthe framework evaluated here. In the comparable NoXi+J\n866\tsettings, the results on this work surpassed the reference\n867\tbaselines, particularly for S/H and S-pred, although higher\n868\t\n869\tscores in some of the remaining event categories were still\n870\treported by the reference methods for specific subsets.\n871\tMethod\n872\t\n873\tCorpus\n874\t\n875\tSubset\n876\t\n877\t\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "db1eddf0-a2c5-4626-8cb5-fbb6af48499e", "uuid": "c19a0a59-92d1-4a3b-babb-a103594b0571", "timestamp": "2026-07-11T16:26:41.499Z", "tool_use_result": {"type": "text", "file": {"filePath": "/inspire/qb-ilm/project/video-generation/chenxie-25019/hyr/iHateTheWorld555.github.io/.claude-review/projects/-inspire-qb-ilm-project-video-generation-chenxie-25019-hyr-iHateTheWorld555-github-io/db1eddf0-a2c5-4626-8cb5-fbb6af48499e/tool-results/bib91ubke.txt", "content": "RĀG CLASSIFICATION OF TAGORE SONGS USING SYMBOLIC MUSIC\nNOTATION AND NOVEL WEIGHTED DISTANCE MEASURES\nCHANDAN MISRA AND SWARUP CHATTOPADHYAY\n\narXiv:2607.07241v2 [cs.SD] 9 Jul 2026\n\nAbstract. Rabindra Sangeet, the body of songs written and composed by Rabindranath Tagore,\noccupies a distinctive position in Indian music by combining poetic expression with melodic ideas\ndrawn from Hindustani rāgs, Bengali folk traditions, tappa, kı̄rtan, Baul music, and Western tunes.\nAlthough many Tagore songs are associated with rāg labels provided by Tagore himself or preserved\nin authoritative notational traditions, rāg identification remains challenging because the songs often\nreflect creative freedom rather than strict adherence to classical rāg grammar.\nThis paper formulates rāg identification in Rabindra Sangeet as a supervised classification problem\nusing symbolic music-sheet notations from Swarabitan. Since large-scale annotated audio or music\ndatasets for Rabindra Sangeet are not readily available, this study constructs a rāg-labelled symbolic\ndataset from notated Tagore songs. The work investigates Euclidean distance and cosine similarity for\nrāg classification and introduces a weighted Euclidean distance measure that assigns greater importance\nto notes belonging to characteristic rāg sequences such as arohana and avarohana. Applied within a\nk-nearest-neighbour framework, the proposed measure improves rāg classification by better capturing\nrāg-specific melodic identity.\n\n1. Introduction\nIndian music has evolved through a continuous interaction between classical discipline, regional expression, devotional imagination, poetic thought, and cultural practice. The Hindustani classical tradition,\nwith its highly developed concepts of rāg and tāla, provides a sophisticated framework for organizing\nmelody, rhythm, mood, and performance. At the same time, Indian musical culture has never remained\nrestricted to the boundaries of formal classical grammar. It has continuously interacted with folk traditions, devotional forms, literary movements, theatre, dance, and regional musical practices.\nWithin this rich musical landscape, Rabindra Sangeet occupies a distinctive and culturally significant\nposition. Composed by Rabindranath Tagore, the Nobel Laureate poet, composer, philosopher, and\nartist, Rabindra Sangeet represents one of the most important song traditions of Bengal. These songs\nform an integral part of Bengali cultural life in India and Bangladesh and continue to hold a central\nplace in artistic, social, educational, and devotional contexts.\nMusically, Tagore’s songs draw from a wide range of sources. Many compositions reveal the influence of\nHindustani classical rāgs and tāla-based structures, while others reflect the melodic character of tappa,\nkı̄rtan, Baul, Bengali folk music, devotional idioms, and Western tunes [1–3]. Tagore did not merely\nreproduce these traditions in a fixed or mechanical manner. Instead, he adapted and transformed them\naccording to the expressive needs of the text, the emotional situation of the song, and his own artistic\nvision. As a result, Rabindra Sangeet retains a deep connection with Indian musical traditions while\ndeveloping an independent musical identity.\nAlthough, the tonal colours of rāgs often provide the emotional foundation of the songs, the use of\nrāg in Rabindra Sangeet is not always identical to its use in formal Hindustani classical performance. In\nmany cases, Tagore employed rāg elements with creative freedom, allowing poetic meaning and emotional\nexpression to guide the musical structure. Some Tagore songs closely follow the characteristic structure\nand melodic behaviour of a particular rāg. Others combine features of two or more rāgs, while some\nsongs are traditionally associated with a rāg but do not strictly follow its grammatical framework [4, 5].\nThe compositional structure of Rabindra Sangeet further increases the difficulty of rāg identification.\nFor a beginner or non-specialist listener, recognizing the rāg from a Tagore song is often difficult because\nthe song may not present the rāg in a direct or conventional manner. A single composition may contain\na long sequence of notes, repeated melodic phrases, expressive variations, and movements that do not\nalways correspond to the strict grammar of a classical rāg. Consequently, predicting the rāg basis of a\nRabindra Sangeet composition is a challenging task. Existing approaches to rāg classification, which are\nDate: June 1, 2017, accepted December 7, 2017.\n2000 Mathematics Subject Classification. Primary xxx, yyyy; Secondary xxxx, yyyy.\nKey words and phrases. Dxxx gxxx, Axxx gxxx.\n1\n\n\f2\n\nCHANDAN MISRA AND SWARUP CHATTOPADHYAY\n\noften designed for classical music performances, cannot be directly applied to Rabindra Sangeet without\ncareful adaptation. This is because Tagore’s songs are highly diverse in melodic construction.\nRāg identification is important for several computational music tasks, including music learning, music\ninformation retrieval, mood-based classification, recommendation, and computational music generation.\nIn the context of Rabindra Sangeet, this task becomes particularly meaningful because many songs are\nassociated with rāg labels, yet their melodic structures often differ from the strict grammar of Hindustani\nclassical compositions. Therefore, identifying the underlying rāg of a Tagore song requires examining its\nmelodic behaviour, including the use of Āroh, Avroh, dominant notes, omitted notes, and the relative\nimportance of notes within the composition.\nHowever, this diversity does not make the problem unsuitable for supervised learning. On the contrary,\nRabindra Sangeet provides an interesting setting for supervised rāg classification because many songs are\nassociated with rāg labels provided by Tagore himself or preserved in authoritative notational traditions.\nThese rāg labels offer a meaningful ground truth for computational analysis. Therefore, the present\nstudy formulates rāg identification as a supervised classification problem, where labelled Tagore songs\nare used to train a model that can learn rāg-specific melodic behaviour from symbolic note sequences.\nAlthough rāg identification can naturally be formulated as a supervised learning problem, the availability of suitable annotated datasets remains a major limitation in the context of Rabindra Sangeet.\nIn many music classification tasks, annotated audio or music datasets [6–8] with reliable class labels\nare used to train supervised models [9–12]. However, such large-scale labelled datasets are not readily\navailable for Rabindra Sangeet. This creates a significant barrier to applying existing data-driven rāg\nclassification techniques directly to Tagore songs.\nTo address this limitation, the present work relies on symbolic music-sheet notations rather than\nannotated audio recordings. The primary source of these notations is Swarabitan, the collection of\nnotated songs written and composed by Rabindranath Tagore. Swarabitan contains a large body of\nRabindra Sangeet compositions along with their musical notations, and therefore provides a structured\nsymbolic representation of the melodic content of Tagore songs.\nThese notated compositions are useful for computational analysis because the melodic content of\neach song can be converted into note sequences and note-frequency distributions. Since many of these\ncompositions are associated with rāg labels provided by Tagore himself or preserved in authoritative\nnotational traditions, they can be used to construct a supervised learning dataset. In this way, the\nabsence of a ready-made annotated audio dataset is addressed by preparing a rāg-labelled symbolic\ndataset from notated Rabindra Sangeet compositions.\nIn this work, we prepare a supervised symbolic dataset of 1000 rāg-labelled Tagore songs from Swarabitan. Each sample in the dataset corresponds to the note-frequency distribution of a composition and is\nassociated with its appropriate rāg label. The construction of this dataset is an important contribution of\nthe work, as it provides a structured ground truth for supervised rāg classification in Rabindra Sangeet.\nA natural approach to rāg identification is to compare a given composition with other compositions\nwhose rāg labels are already known. If two compositions are musically similar, they may be expected\nto share similar rāg characteristics. Therefore, an unknown or test composition can be assigned the rāg\nlabel of its nearest labelled compositions using a distance or similarity-based classifier. In this direction, Euclidean distance and cosine similarity provide simple and widely used measures for quantifying\nsimilarity between compositions represented through note-frequency features.\nHowever, standard distance and similarity measures may not be sufficient for Rabindra Sangeet.\nPreliminary observations show that Euclidean distance and cosine similarity can sometimes produce\ncontradictory or misleading results. In particular, they may assign high similarity or low distance not\nonly to compositions belonging to the same rāg, but also to compositions belonging to different rāgs.\nThis happens because small variations in individual note frequencies may strongly affect the similarity\nscore, while the musically important role of characteristic notes may not be adequately captured. Thus,\ntwo compositions may appear numerically similar even when their rāg identities are different.\nTo address this limitation, the present study introduces a rāg-aware weighted Euclidean distance\nmeasure. The main idea is to assign greater importance to notes that belong to the prescribed Āroh and\nAvroh of a rāg, and comparatively lower importance to other notes. This weighting allows the distance\nmeasure to better reflect rāg-specific melodic identity rather than treating all note-frequency differences\nequally. When used with a k-nearest-neighbour classifier, the weighted distance measure helps improve\nthe distinction between compositions belonging to similar and dissimilar rāgs.\n\n\fSHORT TITLE\n\n3\n\n2. Dataset\n2.1. Dataset Generation. As mentioned earlier, Tagore’s complete collection of songs consists of approximately 2200 compositions. This collection of songs is known as Geetobitan (The Garden of Songs),\nwhile their musical notations are published separately in Swarabitan (The Garden of Notes). Swarabitan,\na book series comprising around 60 volumes, contains the notations of songs from Geetobitan written in\nthe Akarmatrik notation system.\nFor the present study, the dataset was created by randomly selecting 1000 compositions from Swarabitan. The notes of each selected composition were manually stored in a CSV file along with the corresponding rāg label. Therefore, each sample in the dataset represents a single composition from Swarabitan.\nSince Rabindrasangeet is based on the Rāgs of Hindustani Sangeet (with a little blend of folk genres\nlike Baul and Kirtan), the notes of the compositions span over three octaves or Saptak s, namely the\nmiddle or Madhya, upper or Taar, and lower octave or Mandra Saptak. The rāgs also follow the same\nĀroh and Avroh notes of Hindutani Sangeet which depict the sequence of permissible notes in ascending\nand descending pattern respectively. Additionally, they aid in describing the rag’s mood. Each octave\nconsists of 12 notes which generates 36 probable notes for each composition. We have indexed each note\nwith an integer starting from 1 and ending at 36 as given in Table 1.\nSuddha\nSuddha\nKomal\nKomal\nShadaj\nMadhyam\nRishabh Rishabh Gandhar Gandhar\n(S, S, Ṡ)\n(M , M , Ṁ )\n(r, r, ṙ) (R, R, Ṙ) (g, g, ġ) (G, G, Ġ) ˙\n˙\n˙\n˙ 17, 29\nIndices 1, 13, 25 2, 14, 26 3,˙ 15, 27 4,˙ 16, 28 5,\n6, 18, 30\nKomal\nSuddha\nSuddha\nTivr\nKomal\nPancham\nDhaivat\nDhaivat\nNishad\nNishad\nNote Madhyam\n(P , P , Ṗ )\n˙ (D, D, Ḋ) (n, n, ṅ) (N , N , Ṅ )\n(m, m, ṁ) ˙\n(d, d, d)\n˙\n˙\n˙ 22, 34 11,\n˙ 24, 36\nIndices 7, 19, 31 8, 20, 32 9,˙ 21, 33 10,\n23, 35 12,\nNote\n\nTable 1. Notes and indices of lower octave or Mandra Saptak (indices 1 to 12), Middle\noctave or Madhya Saptak (indices 13 to 24), and upper octave or Taar Saptak (indices\n25 to 36)\nOnce such mapping is established we generate the note table for each such 1000 compositions. To\ncreate the final dataset we generate the frequency distribution of each composition which serves as 36\nindependent variables and obtain the rāg of the composition for the dependent variable. Figure 1 shows\nthe overall process of mapping a composition to a frequency table.\n2.2. Summary of the Dataset. As previously mentioned the dataset consists of 36 features corresponding to 36 notes spanning across three octaves for each sample and there are 1000 such samples\nhave been considered for our experimental evaluation. We labeled each such sample with the rāg of the\ncomposition which have also been extracted manually from the book while creating the dataset and can\nbe considered as a ground truth. There are 239 unique rāgs identified in the entire dataset and more than\n50% samples (545 compositions) belong to 227 least frequent rāgs having number of compositions less\nthan 20. Table 1 shows the frequencies of unique rāgs with increasing number of compositions. In other\nwords Table 1 answers the query How many unique rāgs are there having n number of compositions?,\nfor example.\nWhile Table 2a summarizes the distribution of the less frequent rāgs in the dataset, Table 2b presents\nthe opposite view by listing the 12 most frequent rāg labels. This information is important because\nrāgs with very few compositions may not provide sufficient samples to capture a reliable note-frequency\npattern or average distribution for that particular rāg.\nIn Table 2b, we also provide the corresponding Thaat of each rāg. In Hindustani classical music,\na Thaat refers to the parent scale or melodic framework used in Pt. Vishnu Narayan Bhatkhande’s\nsystem for classifying rāgs according to their note structure. Including the Thaat information helps the\nreader understand the broader melodic family to which a rāg belongs. It is also useful for interpreting\nsimilarities between rāgs, since rāgs belonging to the same Thaat may share similar note structures.\nHowever, the entries Baul and Kirtan are marked as NA because they are not classified as rāgs under\nthe Bhatkhande Thaat system. Rather, they represent folk and devotional musical traditions that occur\nfrequently in Rabindra Sangeet but do not necessarily follow a fixed Āroh–Avroh structure associated\nwith a specific Hindustani classical rāg. Therefore, they are retained in the dataset as musical-category\nlabels rather than being assigned to a particular Thaat.\n\n\f4\n\nCHANDAN MISRA AND SWARUP CHATTOPADHYAY\n\n16\n\n14\n\n14\n\n13\n\n13\n\n13\n\n21\n\n21\n\n21\n\n23\n\n25\n\n25\n\n23\n\n28\n\n28\n\n26\n\n25\n\n23\n\n25\n\n25\n\n25\n\n25\n\n25\n\n25\n\n23\n\n28\n\n26\n\n25\n\n26\n\n25\n\n23\n\n25\n\n23\n\n21\n\n23\n\n21\n\n(b) Mapping from actual note to its corresponding integer value\n\n\nMultimodal Voice Activity Projection for Turn-Taking in Social Robots\nwith Voice-Activity-Related Pretrained Encoders\n\narXiv:2607.07294v1 [cs.RO] 8 Jul 2026\n\nAntonio Cano1,2 , Guillermo Pérez1 , Luis Merino2\nAbstract— Turn-taking prediction is a key requirement for\nsocial robots involved in human-human interaction, particularly in mediator settings, where the robot must anticipate\nconversational dynamics rather than merely react to pauses.\nThis work presents a Multimodal Voice Activity Projection\n(MM-VAP) framework that extends the original audio-only\nVAP formulation to synchronized audio-visual inputs while\npreserving its self-supervised future-projection objective. The\nproposed approach builds on pretrained audio-visual backbones\noriginally optimized for speech-related tasks and adapts them\nthrough Low-Rank Adaptation to the multimodal turn-taking\nproblem. After independent speaker encoding, an inter-speaker\nattention stage models the relational dynamics required to\nproject future voice activity. In addition, a semantic consistency\nloss is introduced to regularize the 256-state output space according to higher-level dialogue activity patterns. Experiments\non NoXi and NoXi+J showed improvements over the current\nbaselines, particularly for some turn-taking events. Additional\nevaluation on the Haru EDR corpus further supported the\nsuitability of this direction for mediation-oriented human-robot\ninteraction.\nThe source codes and pretrained models are available at\nhttps://github.com/acano15/MM-VAP.\n\nI. I NTRODUCTION\nTurn-taking is the universal mechanism of human communication for structuring spoken interaction and coordinating\nspeaker and listener roles [1]. To achieve effective Human–Robot Interaction (HRI), conversational robots must account for this human-like coordination across verbal and nonverbal behavior. In social robotics, interaction is inherently\nturn-based [2], so accurate interpretation of conversational\nflow and timing is necessary to enable fluid and effective\ncommunication.\nThis work extends previous research [3] within the Haru\nsocial robot project, specifically when Haru acts as an\nembodied social mediator that supports human-human interactions [4]–[6]. In this scenario, Haru is not conceived as\none of the main interlocutors, but instead as a background\nsocial mediator (Fig. 1) that helps regulate conversational\nflow, balance participation, manage silences, and support\nsocio-emotional behaviors such as active listening, engagement, and empathy. This mediator role motivates the present\n1 Antonio Cano and Guillermo Perez are with 4i Intelligent Insights,\nSeville, Spain. a.cano@4i.ai, g.perez@4i.ai\n3 Antonio Cano is with Universidad de Sevilla, Seville, Spain.\n\nacano4@us.es\n2\n\nLuis Merino is with Universidad Pablo de Olavide, Seville, Spain.\n\nlmercab@upo.es\n3 Randy Gomez is with Honda Research Institute Japan, Saitama, Japan.\n\nr.gomez@jp.honda-ri.com\n\nand Randy Gomez3\n\nFig. 1: Haru operating as social mediator in two-party\ninteraction setting [8].\nresearch toward enabling Haru to better understand and\nmanage the ongoing interaction, with particular emphasis on\nhow the conversational floor evolves over time and anticipate\nwhen it may change.\nNevertheless, current dialogue systems are not yet sufficiently accurate at managing turn-taking, and this remains an\nactive area of research because users frequently experience\nthe effects of such failures. Typical problems include interruptions or overlaps due to speaking before or after a turn\nhas ended, unnaturally long delays caused by late responses,\nand incorrect answers resulting from misunderstanding the\nuser’s input. Furthermore, because human communication is\ninherently multimodal [7], these limitations, together with the\nlack of multimodal perception skills, may cause the robot to\ngaze at the wrong person or respond to irrelevant background\nspeech.\nAddressing this issue requires a structured view of how\nturns are formed, maintained, and exchanged during interaction. In conversation analysis, spoken interaction is\ndescribed in terms of Turn-Constructional Units (TCUs),\nwhose possible completion defines a Transition-Relevant\nPlace (TRP) that may lead to a turn shift, a turn hold,\nor floor closure. Most industrial systems remain reactive\n[9], using heuristic silence-based rules to detect the Endof-Turn (EoT), normally around 700 ms [10]. Studies in\ndialogue systems and dialogue robots [10]–[13] have shown\nthat such approaches are insufficient for modeling conversational dynamics because speakers may produce longer pauses\nwithin their own turn, known as Inter-Pausal Units (IPUs)\n[14]. Human turn-taking in conversations follows a different\nprinciple than current Spoken Dialogue Systems (SDSs).\nA key distinction is that humans do not simply wait for\nexplicit cues indicating that the interlocutor is ready to yield\n\nAccepted preprint. This manuscript has been accepted for presentation at the 35th IEEE International Conference on Robot and Human\nInteractive Communication (RO-MAN 2026). Acceptance notification date: 30 May 2026. The final published version is pending.\n\n\fthe floor; instead, they continuously predict ongoing events\nand adapt their role as listener or speaker accordingly. This\ngenuinely predictive behavior is supported by the temporal\nconstraints of speech generation: producing speech typically\nrequires around 600 ms to 1500 ms [15], [16], and the time\nbetween turns, as well known as Floor Transfer Offset (FTO),\nusually occurs around 200 ms of silence (in some cultures\nmay approach 0 ms [17]). This temporal mismatch indicates\nthat turn-taking depends on prediction, with multimodal cues\nguiding anticipation of TRPs and coordinating responses\nwith minimal delay.\nInspired by this behavior, Predictive Turn-Taking Models (PTTMs) have been proposed as neural models that\ncontinuously project future conversational activity at frame\nlevel, mostly in two-party spoken interaction [10]. Among\ncurrent approaches, Voice Activity Projection (VAP) [18]\nis positioned as one of the most effective formulations for\ncontinuous turn-taking prediction, including real-time implementations. VAP projects frame-by-frame the voice activity\n(VA) of two speakers and models their interaction dynamics\nto predict turn-taking events. More recently, multimodal\nextensions of VAP have become an active and promising\nresearch direction [9], [19]–[21], where the incorporation\nof non-verbal information offers further opportunities for\nimprovement, despite the challenges that still remain in\npractical spoken dialogue system environments.\nTo contribute to this research line, this work proposes\na transformers-based MultiModal Voice Activity Projection\n(MM-VAP) model built on specialized pretrained encoders.\nThe main contributions are the following:\n• An audio-visual MM-VAP architecture that integrates VArelated pretrained backbones while preserving their native representational and fusion capabilities for improved\nVA projection.\n• A parameter-efficient adaptation strategy based on LowRank Adaptation for specializing the encoders to the\ntarget turn-taking task.\n• Improved performance on mediation-relevant turn-taking\nstates, highlighting the benefits of the proposed pipeline.\n• The first application of MM-VAP in a robotics context,\nwith an empirical evaluation of the proposed approach for\npredictive turn-taking in the Haru social mediator setting.\nII. R ELATED W ORK\nTurn-taking prediction has been extensively studied in\nSDS, HRI, and, more recently, in VAP-based approaches.\nThis section reviews the most relevant prior work and the\nkey considerations that motivated the presented approach.\nRecent multimodal speech and language research [22]–\n[28] has shown that large pretrained backbones can be\nefficiently adapted with Low-Rank Adaptation (LoRA), allowing transfer of knowledge to more specific tasks by\nupdating only a small subset of parameters instead of the\nentire model. At the same time, multimodal specialization\n\nstill depends on attention mechanisms to model cross-modal\ndependencies. Based on this, special attention is given to\ntwo backbones: TalkNet [29], which uses cross-attention\nand self-attention for Active Speaker Detection (ASD), and\nWhisperFlamingo [30], which combines pretrained Whisper\nand AV-HuBERT with gated cross-attention for multilingual\nAudio Visual Speech Recognition (AVSR).\nWithin the VAP research line, [18] introduced VAP as\na self-supervised prediction problem that outputs the VA\nof two speakers. The original model combines an encoder\nbased on a pretrained CPC backbone operating on the raw\naudio waveform with a second encoder that incorporates the\ncurrent VA frame and its history, followed by a transformer\nthat projects future VA. This formulation has remained a\ncentral reference for turn-taking modeling in SDSs and\nmost subsequent studies have preserved its core idea with\nonly minor modifications. For example, [31] extended VAP\nto three-party interaction by reducing the projection space\nto two bins per speaker, [32] adapted it to binary and\nthree-class backchannel (BC) prediction and [33] modified\nthe loss function by incorporating BC and EoT terms to\nbalance multitask objectives. Regarding multilinguality, [34]\nshowed that monolingual models generalize poorly to unseen\nlanguages in contrast with training on multiple languages,\nwhose performance was comparable to the original languagespecific implementations. Complementing this finding, [35]\nargued that those cross-lingual differences are better explained by dataset discrepancies, particularly inconsistencies\nin speech segmentation labels, than language itself. Beyond\noffline benchmarks, VAP has also shown practical value,\nas its continuous frame-level formulation and lightweight\ninference make it suitable for real-time (RT) implementation.\nFor instance, [36] demonstrated the feasibility of continuous\nturn-taking prediction by shortening the transformer input\n(1s), with only limited performance degradation. However,\naccording to [13], its effectiveness still depends on sensor\nreliability and synchronization quality.\nIn the field of robotics, turn-taking has shown promising\nimprovements over conventional strategies. The main HRI\nreference remains [37], in which one of the speakers is\nreplaced by the robot’s own voice so that VAP could provide RT turn-taking event predictions for floor management,\ninterruptions and BC. More recently, [38] reformulated the\ntraining with noisy data to improve robustness and latency\nin RT environment and validated it on a dialogue robot\ndeployed in a shopping mall.\nConcerning multimodal VAP, only a few studies have been\nreported so far, all of them extending the original acoustic\nframework to additional modalities under formulations close\nto the original VAP design. The first multimodal VAP solution was presented in [39] with the addition of a non-verbal\nbranch based on gaze, action units, head pose, and articularpoint features. Their results showed that multimodality improved performance across predictive events. This work was\nlater extended in [19] through a broader experimental study,\n\nAccepted preprint. This manuscript has been accepted for presentation at the 35th IEEE International Conference on Robot and Human\nInteractive Communication (RO-MAN 2026). Acceptance notification date: 30 May 2026. The final published version is pending.\n\n\fFig. 2: Proposed MM-VAP architecture for dyadic interaction overview. Blue and red paths indicate the flow from raw inputs\nto latent representations for Speaker 1 and Speaker 2. Snowflake and flame symbols denote frozen and trainable parameters.\nThe bottom-right panel shows how the target turn-taking events are derived from voice activity patterns within wt∆t .\nthe addition of an overlap prediction metric and the evaluation across multiple corpora. An analogous feature-based\ndirection was followed in [9], with facial feature positioning\nas the strongest visual contributor, resulting in improved\nperformance over audio-only baselines. Nevertheless, both\napproaches relied on engineered descriptors rather than\nmodel-based feature extraction. Moving toward multimodal\nbackbone-oriented solutions, the unique approach identified\nwas [20], in which the authors replaced the hand-crafted\nfacial descriptors with pretrained audio (original CPC) and a\nfacial expression encoder (DEFER). However, the selected\nencoders remained generic and their pretraining was not\nrelated to voice activity, which reduced their potential for\nVAP. In addition, because the approach used two separate\nencoders, the inter-modal relation had to be learned from\nscratch.\nMotivated by these limitations, the present work investigates whether multimodal VAP can benefit from specialized\nspeech-activity backbones integrated into its inter-modal\nattention mechanism to obtain richer, more task-relevant\nmultimodal representations.\nIII. P ROPOSED M ETHOD\nThis section describes the proposed multimodal VAP\n(MM-VAP) framework and its complete pipeline, from synchronized audio-visual input sequences to VA and VAP\nstate projection estimation and final inference of turn-taking\nevents.\nA. Multimodal Voice Activity Projection (MM-VAP)\nVAP was formally defined [18] as the task of predicting\n(projecting) the future VA binary state (active/inactive) of\n\neach interlocutor in a dialogue. MM-VAP extends the standard definition by incorporating data from multiple modalities, in this case, audio and visual signals. The projection is\nformulated over a finite temporal horizon ∆t that spans from\nthe current time step t to a future point t + ∆t. Within this\ninterval, the future binary VA of both speakers is considered\njointly, so that future VA is modeled as a single projection\nwindow, wt∆t , that represents the future trajectory of the\ndialogue and the joint VA of both speakers as a whole. The\nchoice of the window length involves a balance because it\nshould be long enough to be able to capture relevant turntaking information but no longer than it attempts to represent\nexcessively complex or unnatural future interaction patterns.\nAs in the original implementation, this window is divided\ninto 4 heterogeneous bins per speaker. The first two bins\nare shorter, representing the immediate present (now), or\nnear future, and the last two bins correspond to longer bins\nthat cover more distant f uture. Since the scenario involves\ntwo speakers, the complete projection window is represented\nby a joint space of 22N = 256 states, in which each state\ncompactly covers every possible configuration of the horizon\ninteraction between the two interlocutors.\nB. Proposed MM-VAP model architecture\nAs shown in Fig. 2, the model is organized in five stages:\npreprocessing, backbone encoding, inter-speaker attention,\nprediction heads with postprocessing.\nFirst, the raw audio-visual streams are segmented in the\nwt∆t centered at each frame step t with ∆t horizon separated\ninto speaker-specific signals. For each speaker i, the audio\nwaveform is transformed into a spectral representation, and\nthe visual stream is processed by the face detection module\nthat extracts the temporally ordered sequence of cropped\nface images. Then, both modalities are synchronized to the\n\nAccepted preprint. This manuscript has been accepted for presentation at the 35th IEEE International Conference on Robot and Human\nInteractive Communication (RO-MAN 2026). Acceptance notification date: 30 May 2026. The final published version is pending.\n\n\fsame temporal resolution and fed together into the pretrained,\nfine-tuned encoder. Inside the encoder, each modality is\nfirst processed by its own corresponding modality encoder\nbranch, yielding speaker representations in their respective\nlatent spaces. The resulting audio and visual embeddings\nare fused with the backbone’s original inter-modal attention\nmechanism, producing an embedding per speaker:\nHi = Attn(Ea (Xia ), Ev (Xiv )), where H i ∈ R256 and\n{Qai = Ea (Xia ), Kiv = Viv = Ev (Xiv )}.\nOnce each H is obtained, the model applies a second\nmultihead cross-attention mechanism between both speakers,\nreferred to as inter-speaker attention, to learn how the current\nmultimodal state of one \u0001participant influences the other.\nz = Φinter-spkrs H(1) , H(2) . This stage allows the model to\nencode turn-taking as a relational process, so the prediction\nis conditioned on both the speaker’s current state and the\nother speaker’s state. The joint representation z is then fed\nto two heads: the first head estimates the multiclass VAP\nstate distribution, and the second head predicts the binary\nVA probabilities. Finally, these outputs are postprocessed\nto compute the target turn-taking event categories from the\npredicted VAP state distribution.\nC. Backbone encoders and LoRA adaptation\nThe current MM-VAP solution is based on the premise that\nmodeling turn-taking is equivalent to predict the evolution\nof the speaker’s VA dynamics from audio-visual cues. This\nwork hypothesized that a pretrained encoder whose original\ntask is closely related to VA would be more suitable as a\nstarting point for MM-VAP than a pretrained generic multimodal encoder. Under this view, the multimodal encoder\nshould provide latent representations that remain strongly\naligned with speech activity and are able to preserve the\ntemporal coordination between audio-visual modalities.\nIn addition, the backbone selection was based on two\ncriteria: first, the backbone should achieve high accuracy\non its original task related to speech activity, and second,\nit should include a robust internal attention mechanism between audio-visual modalities. The architecture is modularly\ndesigned, so any transformer-based backbone that satisfies\nthese conditions could be integrated. In this work, TalkNet\nand WhisperFlamingo were selected because they both meet\nboth requirements and provide well proved pretrained multimodal encoders for ASD and AVSR respectively, which are\nbased on speech activity.\n0\nNevertheless, their original pretrained weights, Wav\n∈\nRdxk , remain specialized for the original task, so an adaptation mechanism is required to redirect their representations\nto the target setting. Given the size and the high variance\nof the original backbones weights, fully fine-tuning the\npretrained model is computationally very inefficient, which\nmotivates the use of Low-Rank Adaptation (LoRA) training\nstrategy. LoRA keeps the original model weights frozen\nand adds trainable low-rank matrices to selected layers to\nadapt the backbone to the MM-VAP objective. This strategy\n\nis computationally more efficient because it approximates\nthe full objective weights (∆W ) by applying the low-rank\ndecomposition of the ∆W into a scalar product of two\nsmaller matrices B ∈ Rdxr and A ∈ Rrxk . Formally, LoRA\ndefines the adapted mapping as:\nα\n0\n(1)\nWAv = WAv\n+ BA, r ≪ min(d, k),\nr\nwhere A and B are trainable low-rank matrices, r is the\nadaptation rank and α is the scaling factor. In this context,\nr controls the flexibility of the adaptation to adapt to the\nVAP objective and α determines how strongly that adaptation\ninfluences the training.\nWithin this framework, LoRA enables the specialization of\nthe pretrained backbone to the MM-VAP objective by building on the capabilities acquired during its original training\nphase and redirecting them toward future VA projection.\nD. Zero-shot turn-taking events inference\nThis work followed the original VAP Self-Supervised\nLearning (SSL) approach [18], in which the training is\nperformed without manual annotations of turn-taking events.\nSpecifically, at each frame, the model predicts a probability\ndistribution over the 256 states, and the turn-taking events are\nobtained in a zero-shot manner by summing the probabilities\nof the states linked to each conversational outcome. This\ninterpretability is enabled by collapsing the fine-grained state\nspace into a simpler bin-level representation that preserves\nthe same VAP state distribution, with four possible cases:\nspeaker 1 active, speaker 2 active, both active, or neither\nactive. Based on this four-way representation, the aggregated\nprobabilities pnow and pf uture summarize speaker activity\nover the near and later regions of the projection window\nand provide the basis for defining each turn-taking event as\nfollows:\n• Shift vs Holds (S/H): measures who are expected to\ntake the floor after a mutual silence. If the same speaker\ncontinues, the event is Hold; if the floor passes to the other\nspeaker, it is Shift.\n• Long vs Shorts (L/S): describes the duration of the utterance after a valid speaker change. Long means that the new\nspeaker keeps speaking for a sustained period, whereas\nShort corresponds to a brief response (Backchannel).\n• Shift prediction (S-pred): checks whether the other\nspeaker is likely to take the floor soon, even though the\ncurrent speaker is still holding it.\n• Backchannel prediction (BC-pred): measures whether\nthe non-active (listener) is likely to produce a short response, without the current speaker releasing the turn.\nE. Loss function\nIn natural dialogue, many individual VAP state configurations are extremely rare (e.g.: alternating speech in unusual\npatterns) and the resulting distribution is therefore inherently unbalanced. Moreover, because multiple microstates\ncorrespond to the same speaker-activity condition, errors\n\nAccepted preprint. This manuscript has been accepted for presentation at the 35th IEEE International Conference on Robot and Human\nInteractive Communication (RO-MAN 2026). Acceptance notification date: 30 May 2026. The final published version is pending.\n\n\fbetween semantically equivalent microstate predictions do\nnot usually affect the final event computation, although they\nstill contribute to the optimization of the 256-state objective.\nTo guide optimization toward speaker-activity patterns that\nare truly relevant for event inference, an additional semantic\nconsistency term (Lsem ) is incorporated into the original loss\nfunction:\nL = LV A + LV AP + µ · Lsem , µ ∈ [0.1, 0.2] (2)\nLV AP is cross-entropy over 256 VAP microstates, LVA is\nmulti-label binary cross-entropy loss for per-speaker VA\noutputs, and µ is an empirically chosen coefficient that\ncontrols the new loss contribution. Lsem is defined as:\n\n\n\n\n0 : spkr1 active\n\n\nX\n1 : No spkrs active\npt (k) , st ∈\nLsem = Et − log\n\n2 : Both spkrs active\n\n\n3 : spkr2 active\n\nk∈Gst\n\n(3)\nwhere pt (k) is the predicted probability of microstate k at\ntime t, st the semantic dialogue states and Gst the set of all\nmicrostates whose current activity matches the same st .\nHence, instead of only discriminating among imbalanced\nand partially redundant microstates, Lsem encourages the\nmodel to assign probability mass to all states that share the\ncorrect dialogue meaning. From an optimization perspective,\nthis term reduces the influence of rare or ambiguous states,\nimproves training stability, and aligns the learned VAP distribution with the speaker-activity patterns used to derive the\ntarget events, leading to more robust predictions throughout\ntraining.\nIV. E XPERIMENTS AND RESULTS\n\nwindow, represented through 256 states computed from four\ntemporal bins per speaker (200, 400, 600, and 800 ms). The\nmodel predicts future VA from synchronized audio-visual\ncontext, and the resulting projections are evaluated against\nthe corresponding zero-shot turn-taking events obtained from\nthe VA annotations, using accuracy and F1-score.\nFor all the experiments, the data are split at the session\nlevel into 80 % for training, 10 % for validation, and 10\n% for testing. The datasets were selected for their multilingual coverage and their suitability for the mediator-oriented\ninteraction setting:\n1) NoXi [40]: NOvice eXpert Interaction (NoXi) is a\nmultilingual multimodal corpus of screen-mediated dyadic\ninteractions between an expert and a novice. It captures natural knowledge-sharing conversations in a video-conferencelike setting, where both participants are recorded in separate\nrooms with synchronized audio, video, and depth streams.\nThe original corpus contains 84 sessions and around 25 hours\nof data collected in France, Germany, and the UK, mainly\nin English, French, and German. NoXi+J [41] extends this\nsetup with 48 Japanese and 18 Chinese sessions under the\nsame protocol, resulting in a total of 150 sessions and about\n41 hours of multimodal interaction data.\n2) EDR [8]: Empathetic Dialogues with a Robot (EDR)\nconsists of semi-structured speaker–listener interactions conducted in the presence of Haru, in which the robot frames\neach exchange by delivering an introduction and an emotionbased prompt in English, while the humans carry the conversation (see Fig. 1). The dialogues were derived from reallife situations with 79 conversations, 214 exchanges, and 428\nlabeled utterances.\n\nA. Experimental setup and datasets\nB. Results\nThe experimental protocol was based on the original\nVAP framework, extending it from an acoustic-only setting\nto a multimodal formulation while preserving the same\nself-supervised projection objective. The input consists of\nsynchronized 10s context window extracted with a 0.5s\nslide, prepared according to backbone requirements: audio\nencoded as Log-Mel spectrograms and the visual stream\nas detected faces sequence resized to 112×112 grayscale\nframes. The prediction target is set as 2s future voice activity\n\nLanguage\nEnglish\nGerman\nFrench\nJapanese\nChinese\n\nBackbone\nTalkNet\nWhisperFlamingo\nTalkNet\nWhisperFlamingo\nTalkNet\nWhisperFlamingo\nTalkNet\nWhisperFlamingo\nTalkNet\nWhisperFlamingo\n\nThe following results correspond to experiments designed\nto evaluate VA-related pretrained backbones adapted with\nLoRA within their attention mechanisms, in comparison with\nmore generic pretrained backbones and non-pretrained variants presented in Section II. All experiments were conducted\nunder the same data distribution and evaluation conditions,\nwith particular emphasis on mediation events relevant to\nVA projection. The LoRA adapter parameters were kept\n\nTurn-taking Events (Accuracy / F1)\nS/H\nS/L\nS-pred\nBC-pred\n0.87 ± 0.03 / 0.86 ± 0.01 0.88 ± 0.01 / 0.92 ± 0.01 0.88 ± 0.01 / 0.88 ± 0.01 0.30 ± 0.01 / 0.41 ± 0.01\n0.82 ± 0.08 / 0.82 ± 0.09 0.84 ± 0.02 / 0.89 ± 0.02 0.97 ± 0.04 / 0.97 ± 0.04 0.34 ± 0.02 / 0.45 ± 0.02\n0.89 ± 0.01 / 0.89 ± 0.01 0.87 ± 0.01 / 0.91 ± 0.01 0.94 ± 0.01 / 0.94 ± 0.00 0.33 ± 0.01 / 0.41 ± 0.01\n0.82 ± 0.04 / 0.82 ± 0.04 0.87 ± 0.01 / 0.91 ± 0.01 0.97 ± 0.02 / 0.97 ± 0.02 0.35 ± 0.02 / 0.43 ± 0.03\n0.87 ± 0.03 / 0.87 ± 0.03 0.82 ± 0.03 / 0.88 ± 0.02 0.89 ± 0.05 / 0.89 ± 0.05 0.47 ± 0.03 / 0.56 ± 0.03\n0.84 ± 0.07 / 0.84 ± 0.07 0.85 ± 0.01 / 0.89 ± 0.01 0.96 ± 0.03 / 0.96 ± 0.03 0.42 ± 0.03 / 0.52 ± 0.03\n0.77 ± 0.01 / 0.77 ± 0.01 0.76 ± 0.01 / 0.83 ± 0.01 0.81 ± 0.01 / 0.80 ± 0.01 0.57 ± 0.01 / 0.64 ± 0.01\n0.86 ± 0.03 / 0.87 ± 0.03 0.72 ± 0.01 / 0.80 ± 0.01 0.86 ± 0.02 / 0.86 ± 0.02 0.56 ± 0.03 / 0.62 ± 0.03\n0.85 ± 0.01 / 0.85 ± 0.01 0.77 ± 0.01 / 0.79 ± 0.01 0.90 ± 0.01 / 0.90 ± 0.01 0.77 ± 0.01 / 0.77 ± 0.01\n0.85 ± 0.01 / 0.85 ± 0.01 0.81 ± 0.04 / 0.84 ± 0.04 0.94 ± 0.01 / 0.94 ± 0.01 0.57 ± 0.01 / 0.57 ± 0.01\n\nTABLE I: Per-language results on the evaluated corpora. Each cell reports Acc/F1 for the corresponding turn-taking event.\nAccepted preprint. This manuscript has been accepted for presentation at the 35th IEEE International Conference on Robot and Human\nInteractive Communication (RO-MAN 2026). Acceptance notification date: 30 May 2026. The final published version is pending.\n\n\ffixed across experiments to avoid biasing the final outcome\ncomparison. The selection of parameter values was based on\ntheir original performance and the proximity to the original\ntasks for VA projection. In consequence, α = 16 and r = 16\nfor TalkNet and α = 64 and r = 32 for WhisperFlamingo,\nseeking deeper adaptation. Regarding the hyperparameters,\nthe models were trained for 8 epochs, a linear scheduler\nfor the learning rate with initial value µ = 0.009 and the\ncallbacks needed for stable optimization.\nTable I summarizes the language-wise results obtained on\nNoXi+J with the two main pretrained backbones adapted\nwith LoRA. Reported values are represented by the mean ±\nstandard deviation of accuracy and F1-score over a 4-fold\ncross-validation. The results show consistent performance\nacross languages, with similar distribution patterns. WhisperFlamingo achieved the highest S-pred scores for English\nand German, while TalkNet obtained the best S/H score for\nGerman and the top BC-pred score for Chinese. In contrast,\nperformance on Japanese remained the lowest overall. Across\nthe remaining languages, TalkNet generally outperformed in\nS/H and BC-pred metrics, whereas WhisperFlamingo yielded\nsuperior results in S/L and S-pred.\nTable II come from models trained with different combinations of NoXi+J languages set. In addition to the two main\npretrained backbones, a third reference model integrating\nCPC for audio and 3DResNet for video was included as\na non-pretrained baseline for comparison, given its wellestablished strong performance on VA tasks. Across all\nconfigurations, the pretrained variants consistently outperformed this reference. WhisperFlamingo tended to report the\nstrongest S-pred values, with similar results for S/H across\nboth backbones.\nCorpus\n\nBackbone\n\nTurn-taking Events (F1)\nS/L\n\nS-pred\n\nBC-pred\n\nNoXi\n\nCPC+3DResNet 0.64 0.70\nTalkNet\n0.94 0.93\nWhisperFlamingo 0.97 0.91\n\nS/H\n\n0.65\n0.91\n0.97\n\n0.33\n0.42\n0.45\n\nNew NoXi+J\n(Chin + Jap)\n\nCPC+3DResNet 0.50 0.61\nTalkNet\n0.84 0.82\nWhisperFlamingo 0.85 0.80\n\n0.51\n0.87\n0.93\n\n0.55\n0.62\n0.66\n\nNoXi+J (All)\n\nCPC+3DResNet 0.55 0.59\nTalkNet\n0.85 0.85\nWhisperFlamingo 0.81 0.86\n\n0.58\n0.89\n0.90\n\n0.39\n0.62\n0.44\n\nTABLE II: Experiments on the combined NoXi+J language\nset using pretrained and baseline backbones.\nTable III compares the F1-scores reported in previous\nrelated work on different corpora with those obtained in this\nstudy. The first method’s results were limited to Shift/Hold\nevents, whereas the other two are directly comparable to\nthe framework evaluated here. In the comparable NoXi+J\nsettings, the results on this work surpassed the reference\nbaselines, particularly for S/H and S-pred, although higher\n\nscores in some of the remaining event categories were still\nreported by the reference methods for specific subsets.\nMethod\n\nCorpus\n\nSubset\n\n", "numLines": 877, "startLine": 1, "totalLines": 877}}}
