re Khamaj composition comp22\n1390\tkh(p) , a non-pure Khamaj\n1391\t35\n1392\tcomposition compkh(np) , and a pure Bhairavi composition comp43\n1393\tbh(p) . The prescribed\n1394\tKhamaj note indices are highlighted in blue, while the deviated note index in the nonpure Khamaj composition is highlighted in red. Normalized ordinary Euclidean distance\n1395\tgives a misleading ordering by placing the pure Khamaj composition closer to the pure\n1396\tBhairavi composition than to the non-pure Khamaj composition.\n1397\t(2) To support the second case, we consider two compositions belonging to rāg Bhairavi. Both\n1398\tcompositions are non-pure, i.e., they do not strictly follow the prescribed Āroh and Avroh pattern\n1399\tof rāg Bhairavi. However, their notes are distributed across different octaves in a non-overlapping\n1400\tmanner. That is,\n1401\tIcomp312\n1402\t∩ Icomp415\n1403\t= ∅.\n1404\tbh(np)\n1405\tbh(np)\n1406\tSince both compositions belong to rāg Bhairavi, their similarity is expected to be high from a\n1407\trāg-level perspective. However, due to the non-overlapping nature of their note-index positions\n1408\tacross the three octaves, the cosine similarity becomes zero, as shown in Table 5. This example\n1409\tfurther indicates that cosine similarity may fail to capture rāg-level similarity when octave-wise\n1410\tnote positions differ significantly.\n1411\t\n1412\t\fSHORT TITLE\n1413\t\n1414\t9\n1415\t\n1416\tLower Octave or Mandra Saptak\n1417\tNote Index\n1418\t\n1419\t1\n1420\t\n1421\t2\n1422\t\n1423\t3\n1424\t\n1425\t4\n1426\t\n1427\t5\n1428\t\n1429\t6\n1430\t\n1431\t7\n1432\t\n1433\t8\n1434\t\n1435\t9\n1436\t\n1437\t10\n1438\t\n1439\t11\n1440\t\n1441\t12\n1442\t\n1443\tcomp312\n1444\tbh(np)\n1445\t\n1446\t0\n1447\t\n1448\t0\n1449\t\n1450\t0\n1451\t\n1452\t0\n1453\t\n1454\t0\n1455\t\n1456\t0\n1457\t\n1458\t0\n1459\t\n1460\t0\n1461\t\n1462\t0\n1463\t\n1464\t0\n1465\t\n1466\t0\n1467\t\n1468\t0\n1469\t\n1470\tcomp415\n1471\tbh(np)\n1472\t\n1473\t0\n