o the same rāg, their non-zero note\n1670\tindices occur in non-overlapping octave-wise positions, as highlighted in blue. Consequently, the cosine similarity between them becomes zero.\n1671\t\n1672\t4.2. Comparison between compositions belonging to different rāgs. A similar issue arises when\n1673\tcomputing the similarity between compositions belonging to different rāgs. Since rāgs belonging to\n1674\tthe same Thaat may exhibit similar melodic structures, we selected five rāgs, namely Bhairavi, Bihag,\n1675\tKhamaj, Kafi, and Kedara, each belonging to a different Thaat, as shown in Table 2b.\n1676\tSimilar to the experiment conducted for compositions belonging to the same rāg, we visualize the\n1677\tsimilarity between compositions belonging to different rāgs by computing the mean cosine similarity of\n1678\teach composition with all compositions of another rāg. The resulting plots are shown in Figure 5. Each\n1679\tsubfigure in Figure 5 is overplotted with a red horizontal line, which represents the mean similarity value\n1680\tfor the corresponding pair of rāgs.\n1681\t\n1682\tFigure 5. Mean cosine similarity scores between compositions belonging to different\n1683\trāgs. The selected rāgs are Bhairavi, Bihag, Khamaj, Kafi, and Kedara, each shown\n1684\tin pairwise comparison. The x-axis represents the composition index, while the y-axis\n1685\trepresents the mean cosine similarity with compositions of the other rāg. The horizontal\n1686\tred line shows the average similarity score for each rāg pair.\n1687\tThe mean similarity score indicated by the red horizontal line shows that most of the similarity scores\n1688\tbetween compositions belonging to different rāgs lie above 0.62, which is a considerably high value in\n1689\tterms of cosine similarity. For example, the mean similarity score between rāg Bihag and rāg Kedara is\n1690\t\n1691\t\f10\n1692\t\n1693\tCHANDAN MISRA AND SWARUP CHATTOPADHYAY\n1694\t\n1695\t0.79. Such a high similarity value between compositions of two different rāgs is not generally expected\n1696\tfrom a musical point of view.\n1697\tThis behaviour can be further understood through a representative example involving pure compositions. We consider one pure composition from rāg Bhairavi, namely comp43\n1698\tbh(p) , and three pure composi20\n1699\t21\n1700\ttions from rāg Khamaj, namely comp17\n1701\t,\n1702\tcomp\n1703\t,\n1704\tand\n1705\tcomp\n1706\t.\n1707\tThe\n1708\tnote-frequency distributions\n1709\tkh(p)\n1710\tkh(p)\n1711\tkh(p)\n1712\tof these compositions and the corresponding cosine similarity scores are shown in Table 6.\n1713\tLower Octave or Mandra Saptak\n1714\tNote Index\n1715\t\n1716\t1\n1717\t\n1718\t2\n1719\t\n1720\t3\n1721\t\n1722\t4\n1723\t\n1724\t5\n1725\t\n1726\t6\n1727\t\n1728\t7\n1729\t\n1730\t8\n1731\t\n1732\t9\n1733\t\n1734\t10\n1735\t\n1736\t11\n1737\t\n1738\t12\n1739\t\n1740\tcomp43\n1741\tbh(p)\n1742\t\n1743\t0\n1744\t\n1745\t0\n1746\t\n1747\t0\n1748\t\n1749\t0\n1750\t\n1751\t0\n1752\t\n1753\t0\n1754\t\n1755\t0\n1756\t\n1757\t0\n1758\t\n1759\t0\n1760\t\n1761\t0\n1762\t\n1763\t0\n1764\t\n1765\t0\n1766\t\n1767\tcomp17\n1768\tkh(p)\n1769\t\n1770\t0\n1771\t\n1772\t0\n1773\t\n1774\t0\n1775\t\n1776\t0\n1777\t\n1778\t0\n1779\t\n1780\t0\n1781\t\n1782\t0\n1783\t\n1784\t0\n1785\t\n1786\t0\n1787\t\n1788\t0\n1789\t\n1790\t0\n1791\t\n1792\t0\n1793\t\n1794\tcomp20\n1795\tkh(p)\n1796\t\n1797\t0\n1798\t\n1799\t0\n1800\t\n1801\t0\n1802\t\n1803\t0\n1804\t\n1805\t0\n1806\t\n1807\t0\n1808\t\n1809\t0\n1810\t\n1811\t0\n1812\t\n1813\t0\n1814\t\n1815\t0\n1816\t\n1817\t0\n1818\t\n1819\t0\n1820\t\n1821\tcomp21\n1822\tkh(p)\n1823\t\n1824\t0\n1825\t\n1826\t0\n1827\t\n1828\t0\n1829\t\n1830\t0\n1831\t\n1832\t0\n1833\t\n1834\t0\n1835\t\n1836\t0\n1837\t\n1838\t0\n1839\t\n1840\t0\n1841\t\n1842\t0\n1843\t\n1844\t0\n1845\t\n1846\t0\n1847\t\n1848\tMiddle Octave or Madhya Saptak\n1849\tNote Index\n1850\t\n1851\t13\n1852\t\n1853\t14\n1854\t\n1855\t15\n1856\t\n1857\t16\n1858\t\n1859\t17\n